[[File:India1765.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Map of India (1765) shows [[Awadh|Oudh]], the [[Doab]] (the region in present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]] between the [[Ganges]] and [[Jumna]] rivers), [[Rohilkhand]], the [[History of Delhi#17th century to 19th century|Delhi territories]], eastern [[Punjab region|Punjab]], [[Rajputana]] and [[Kashmir]], all affected by the ''Chalisa'' famine.]]
The '''Chalisa famine''' of 1783–84 in the [[Indian subcontinent]] followed unusual [[El Niño]] events that began in 1780 and caused droughts throughout the region.<ref name=grove-elnino-80>{{Harvnb|Grove|2007|p=80}}</ref>  ''Chalisa'' (literally, "of the fortieth" in [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]]) refers to the [[Vikram Samvat]] calendar year 1840 (1783).<ref>{{Harvnb|Bayly|2002|p=503}}</ref>  The famine affected many parts of [[North India]], especially the [[History of Delhi#17th century to 19th century|Delhi territories]], present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]], Eastern [[Punjab region|Punjab]], [[Rajputana]], and [[Kashmir]], then all ruled by different Indian rulers.<ref name=igi-III-502>{{Harvnb|Imperial Gazetteer of India vol. III|1907|p=502}}</ref>  The ''Chalisa'' was preceded by a  famine in the previous year, 1782–83, in South India, including [[Chennai|Madras City]] and surrounding areas (under [[British East India Company]]  rule) and in the extended [[Kingdom of Mysore]] (under the rule of [[Hyder Ali|Haider Ali]] and [[Tipu Sultan]]).

Together the two famines may have depopulated many regions of India, including, for example, 17 per cent of the villages in the [[Sirkali]] region of present-day [[Tamil Nadu]],<ref name=grove-elnino-80/> 60 per cent of the villages in the middle [[Doab]] of present-day [[Uttar Pradesh]],<ref>{{Harvnb|Bayly|2002|p=90}}</ref> and over 30 per cent of the villages in the regions around Delhi.<ref>{{Harvnb|Stokes|1975|pp=508–509}}</ref>  It is thought that up to 11 million people may have died in the two famines.<ref name=grove-elnino-80/>

