{{Globalize/US |date=June 2016}}
A '''medical data breach''' is a [[data breach]] of health information, and could include either the personal health information of any individual's [[electronic health record]] or [[medical billing]] information from their [[health insurance]].
==Black market for health data== In February 2015 an [[NPR]] report claimed that [[organized crime]] networks had ways of selling health data in the [[black market]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2015/02/13/385901377/the-black-market-for-stolen-health-care-data |title=The Black Market For Stolen Health Care Data : All Tech Considered : NPR |first=Aarti |last=Shahani |work=npr.org |date=13 February 2015 |accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>
In 2015 a [[Beazley Group]] staffperson estimated that medical records could sell on the black market for {{US$|40}}-50.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/06/business/experts-suspect-lax-security-left-anthem-vulnerable-to-hackers.html?_r=0 |title=Anthem Hacking Points to Security Vulnerability of Health Care Industry |first=Reed |last=Abelson |first2=Matthew |last2=Goldstein |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 February 2015 |publisher=[[New York Times Company|NYTC]] |location=[[New York, NY|New York]] |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>
Crime is the primary cause of medical data breaches.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://royaljay.com/security/healthcare-data-breach/ |title=Healthcare data breaches present a $6 billion threat |first=Robbie |last=Richards |work=royaljay.com |date=16 November 2015 |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref>
==How data is lost== Theft, [[data loss]], hacking, and unauthorized account access are ways in which medical data breaches happen.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/08/19/health-care-data-breaches-have-hit-30m-patients-and-counting/ |title=Health care data breaches have hit 30M patients and counting |first=Jason |last=Millman |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=19 August 2014 |publisher=[[Washington Post Company|WPC]] |location=[[Washington, DC|Washington DC]] |issn=0190-8286 |accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>
==List of data breaches== {{See also|List of data breaches}} *In 2018, [[Social Indicators Research]] published the scientific evidence of 173,398,820 (over 173 million) individuals affected in USA from October 2008 (when the data were collected) to September 2017 (when the statistical analysis took place).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11205-018-1837-z | title=Electronic Health Record Breaches as Social Indicators | accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref> *In 2015, [[Anthem Inc.]] lost data for 37 million people in the [[Anthem medical data breach]] *In 2014 4.5 million people using Complete Health Systems had their data stolen<ref name="Fischer 2014"/> *In 2013-14 1 million people using Montana Department of Public Health and Human Services had their data stolen<ref name="Fischer 2014"/> *In 2013 4 million people using Advocate Health and Hospitals Corporation had their data stolen<ref name="Fischer 2014"/> *In 2011 4.9 million users of [[Tricare]] services had their data stolen due to an employee error by [[Science Applications International Corporation]]<ref name="Fischer 2014">{{cite web |url= http://www.healthline.com/health-news/seven-biggest-health-data-breaches-092814 |title=The 7 Biggest Health Data Breaches in the US (So Far) |first=Kristen |last=Fischer |work=healthline.com |date=28 September 2014 |accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref> *In 2011 1.9 million people using [[Health Net]] had their data stolen<ref name="Fischer 2014"/> *In 2011 1 million people using [[Nemours Foundation]] had their data stolen<ref name="Fischer 2014"/> *In 2010 6800 people using [[New York-Presbyterian Hospital]] and [[Columbia University Medical Center]] had their data breached. In response, those organizations agreed to pay the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] a {{US$|4.8}} million dollar fine.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ihealthbeat.org/articles/2014/5/8/columbia-medical-center-hospital-to-pay-4point8m-fine-for-data-breach |title=Columbia Medical Center, Hospital To Pay $4.8M Fine for Data Breach |website=iHealthBeat |publisher=[[California HealthCare Foundation]] |date=8 May 2014 |accessdate=17 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207081508/http://www.ihealthbeat.org/articles/2014/5/8/columbia-medical-center-hospital-to-pay-4point8m-fine-for-data-breach |archive-date=7 February 2016 }}</ref> *In 2009 1 million people using [[BlueCross BlueShield of Tennessee]] had their data stolen<ref name="Fischer 2014"/>
==Regulation== In the United States, the [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act]] and [[Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act]] require companies to report data breaches to affected individuals and the [[United States Federal Government|federal government]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Office of Civil Rights |date=26 July 2013 |title=Breach Notification Rule |website=U.S. Department of Health & Human Services |url=https://www.hhs.gov/ocr/privacy/hipaa/administrative/breachnotificationrule/ }}</ref>
